chunks.translated_text:
To the Celestial Bureaus,

With grace, I implore the Most High Lord Lao, the Most High Elder, the Heavenly Masters, the Female Masters, the Three Masters, and the Lady of the Gates, along with the Lords of the Five Qi, to take heed of this humble servant’s memorial and convey it in due time to the Heavenly Palace. May the true qi descend and flow, sheltering this disciple, his household—both high and low, free and bound—so that all may dwell in peace without harm, forever preserving primordial auspiciousness.

For this disciple and his entire household, may all profound calamities, heavy obstacles, and grievous illnesses be swiftly dispelled, leaving no trace. May wandering and malevolent spirits be eradicated, the household abide in tranquility, and evil gods and wicked ghosts flee to distant realms, ceasing all scheming. May all movements and passages be guarded by benevolent spirits, water and fire be extinguished, metal and stone be sundered. With boundless gratitude, I humbly invoke and beseech:

From the East, the Lord of Life-Calculation of the Nine Yi, with one hundred and twenty officers and generals;
From the South, the Lord of Life-Calculation of the Eight Man, with one hundred and twenty officers and generals;
From the West, the Lord of Life-Calculation of the Six Rong, with one hundred and twenty officers and generals;
From the North, the Lord of Life-Calculation of the Five Di, with one hundred and twenty officers and generals;
From the Center, the Lord of Life-Calculation of the Three Qin and Earthly Stem Wu-Ji, with three hundred and ninety thousand officers and generals.

May all the celestial officers, generals, officials, and soldiers now invoked descend as one to extract the hun and po souls of this disciple, lest they remain trapped within the stellar palaces—whether in Horn, Neck, Root, Room, Heart, Tail, Winnowing Basket, Dipper, Ox, Woman, Emptiness, Danger, House, Wall, Straddler, Bond, Stomach, Pleiades, Net, Turtle Beak, Well, Ghost, Willow, Star, Spread, Wings, Chariot, or any of the Twenty-Eight Constellations and Thirty-Five Stellar Offices. May they descend as one to liberate this disciple and his household—both high and low—from the celestial nets above and the earthly snares below, dispelling calamities, transcending misfortunes, and severing all ties with malevolent spirits. May the afflicted recover, their sustenance flow freely, their complexion restore, their countenance return, the Four Great Elements harmonize, and their bodies be restored to their original state. May every member of the household—both high and low, free and bound—receive protection, dwell in safety without harm, and encounter only primordial auspiciousness. With profound gratitude for this boundless grace, I humbly invoke:

The Great General of the First Month, Yin, for Unbinding and Liberation, with one hundred thousand soldiers;
The Great General of the Second Month, Mao, for Unbinding and Liberation, with one hundred thousand soldiers;
The Great General of the Third Month, Chen, for Striking and Liberation, with one hundred thousand soldiers;
The Great General of the Fourth Month, Si, for Unbinding and Liberation, with one hundred thousand soldiers;
The Great General of the Fifth Month, Wu, for Striking and Liberation, with one hundred thousand soldiers;
The Great General of the Sixth Month, Wei, for Unbinding and Liberation, with one hundred thousand soldiers;
The Great General of the Seventh Month, Shen, for Striking and Liberation, with one hundred thousand soldiers;
The Great General of the Eighth Month, You, for Unbinding and Liberation, with one hundred thousand soldiers;
The Great General of the Ninth Month, Xu, for Unbinding and Liberation, with one hundred thousand soldiers;
The Great General of the Tenth Month, Hai, for Striking and Liberation, with one hundred thousand soldiers;
The Great General of the Eleventh Month, Zi, for Unbinding and Liberation, with one hundred thousand soldiers;
The Great General of the Twelfth Month, Chou, for Unbinding and Liberation, with one hundred thousand soldiers.

May all the generals, officers, and soldiers of the Twelve Months for Unbinding and Liberation now invoked descend as one to dissolve the profound calamities and grave illnesses of this disciple and his household. May all misfortunes of the year, the month, the day, and the hour be dispelled by the true qi, transcended, and left behind, forever preserving primordial auspiciousness.

I further beseech the One Thousand Two Hundred Celestial Immortals of the Northern Realm for Dispelling Calamities and Curing Illnesses; twelve pure youths and maidens; the Lord of the Southern Prosperity Palace for Extracting Hun and Po Souls from the Rivers and Lochs, with one thousand two hundred soldiers; one hundred thousand Celestial Physicians for Curing Illnesses; and one hundred thousand Earthly Physicians for Curing Illnesses. May they descend as one to liberate this disciple and his household—both high and low—from the nets and snares, transcending calamities and misfortunes. May the three hun and seven po souls be extracted and restored to the body, fully replenished. May calamities be transcended, illnesses dispelled, leaving no trace. May the spirits of the long-departed, the recently deceased, and the externally ascended be banished to distant realms, their malevolent schemes utterly eradicated. May dreams be true and pure, the household tranquil, and every member of the family—both high and low—bathed in clarity and auspiciousness, dwelling in safety without harm.

I prostrate myself and beseech the true officers, generals, officials, and soldiers of the Great Dao to act on behalf of this disciple and his household before the Three Officials of Heaven, Earth, and Water; the Five Peaks and Four Waterways; the Three Rivers and Four Seas; and the hundred ghostly prisons. Seek out this disciple and his household—both high and low—for any misfortunes of exhausted lifespan, the encroachment of baleful stars, the entanglements of the Primordial Hour, the clashes of the Five Phases, or any calamities from the first to the ninth, up to the one hundred and twenty celestial punishments. Dispel and liberate their hun and po souls, restoring them to the body, that they may swiftly recover. If they cannot be found, summon and inquire of the ancestral dead in the Three Mounds and Five Tombs. Seek the three hun and seven po souls of this disciple, or the three hun and fourteen po souls of this female disciple, and restore them to the body. If they still cannot be found, summon and inquire within the Twenty-Four Prisons of Mount Tai to retrieve these hun and po souls and restore them to the body.

May all profound calamities and grave misfortunes, the thousand illnesses and myriad pains, be swiftly dispelled, leaving no trace. May life be preserved whole, restored to its original state. May the four limbs and five organs, the three palaces and six viscera, the seven orifices and protective qi, the three hundred and sixty bones, the one thousand two hundred forms and shadows, the twelve thousand essences of light, and the five-colored lapis lazuli—red and white within the body—be replenished if depleted, their measures increased. May short lifespans be lengthened, their allotments augmented. Where inconvenience persists, transform it: turn short into long, blue into yellow. May lifespan be prolonged, calamities forever transcended, and all illnesses severed. May the spirits of the long-departed, the recently deceased, and the externally ascended turn toward benevolence, joining in protection, ceasing all entanglement. May the household dwell in peace, the residence remain pure, all movements and passages flow unimpeded, and every desire be fulfilled. May this humble servant and his household receive boundless grace, their prayers answered.

May the myriad-year Dao and the seed-people of the world enjoy prosperity in all their comings and goings, with auspicious divinations and dreams, harmony in public and private affairs, and ever-extending years of fortune. For all meritorious and diligent heavenly officials, lords, generals, officers, and soldiers, may their merits be reported and promotions granted in accordance with the Three Assemblies’ comprehensive statutes, that their vows and pledges may not be betrayed. With profound grace, may the Most High review and govern these matters.

Your servant, with reverence and trepidation, bows his head and prostrates himself, kneeling twice to make this known: On behalf of the official so-and-so, whose household has suffered misfortune, I distinguish and enumerate the calamities and adversities, and humbly present a petition—a *Great Petition for Dissolving Disasters and Crossing Adversity*—to the heavenly officials, officers, and soldiers, to be submitted to the Bureau of [such-and-such]. Awaiting your decree, I am filled with awe and fear, bowing my head and prostrating myself twice to make this entreaty.

---

*Scroll Three of the Most High’s Proclamations of Earnest Assistance in Transformation concludes.*
*Scroll Four of the Most High’s Proclamations of Compassionate Assistance in Transformation begins.*

**Petition of the Six Harmonies’ Life-Calculation, Upper Grade of the Primordial Sovereign**
Composed by Master Guangcheng, Du Guangting

From the humble position of [such-and-such], with reverence and trepidation, bowing my head and prostrating myself twice, I humbly submit this petition: Your disciple [so-and-so], having recited the full litany of grievances, states that of late, his household has been afflicted with misfortune—his dwelling plagued by inauspicious vacuity, his dreams tangled and disordered, and all affairs devoid of good fortune. Today, I knock my head to the ground and lay forth these supplications, beseeching that your disciple’s life-calculation be extended, his years increased, his lifespan lengthened, and all obstructions and harms dissolved. May the year, month, and day of his birth be examined and stabilized, disasters dissolved, and adversities crossed, that his body and life may be safeguarded.

Yet your disciple, though but a humble straw-dog of lowly substance, has presumptuously been granted the honor of a most noble existence. Though his years be as fleeting as the morning mushroom, he has fortuitously encountered the true and orthodox Dao. His ancestors revered and honored the Mysterious Gate; his descendants, in unbroken succession, have pledged their lives to the Most High Great Dao, submitting to the jurisdiction of the Lords and Elders. He has been blessed with their compassionate protection, a debt as weighty as the high heavens, and has relied upon their nurturing cultivation, a grace as profound as the vast earth.

Yet your disciple was born amid the Five Turbidities, his fate entwined with the Three Calamities. His perceptions are stained by the Six Passions, his karma entangled with the Nine Adversities. His heart and spirit are confused and troubled, his wisdom dim and clouded. In his devotion to the Dao, he has often strayed from its true teachings, causing the numinous spirits to withhold their protection and ghostly *qi* to encroach upon him. For years now, he has known only hardship and setbacks. All he has witnessed and encountered has been inauspicious, with no recourse for redress. When afflictions arise, disasters multiply, and lawsuits befall him, his dwelling is never at peace, and his household suffers from emaciation and illness.

Since the beginning of this year, as spring and summer have arrived, flocks of birds have cried out in disarray, their voices inharmonious and unceasing. His dreams have been devoid of goodness, and decline, hardship, and disaster have arisen. His aspirations have all strayed from their original intent. Perhaps it is your disciple and his wife who are afflicted, or perhaps his fate and lifespan are in conflict. The birth month and the *zi* and *wu* hours clash; the birth day clashes with his body. There is discord with the birth year, and his calculations are unstable. The birth month, too, is irregular, and the stars and celestial reckonings of his destined hour are unsteady. Once this is determined, it will bind him for all his life, and the cycles of his fate will be fixed forever.

If it is not a convergence of calamities and taboos, then it is his dwelling that has suffered disaster. Perhaps he has encountered a year of the Seven Harms, or a year of the Five Ghosts. Perhaps it is a month of the Four Killers, or a time of the Six Harms. Perhaps he faces the anxieties of the Eight Difficulties, or the taboos of the Seven Injuries. Perhaps he is beset by the misfortunes of the Nine Pitfalls, or the disasters of the Ten Severances. Or perhaps your disciple has moved his residence at an inauspicious time, failing to choose an auspicious day, so that his comings and goings miss the proper hours. His endeavors have offended malevolent spirits; his mornings and evenings are disordered. He has transgressed against the heavenly Dao, and there is no means to avert the resulting misfortune.

Perhaps his wife and children are afflicted, or his parents are harmed by punishment. His fate is in conflict, his year clashes with Jupiter. Perhaps he has entered the Gate of Heaven, or encountered the dire region of the Nine Adversities of Absolute Yang. Perhaps he has approached the Gate of Earth, or the inauspicious place where Absolute Yin enters the tomb. Above, he is entangled in the Heavenly Net; below, he is ensnared in the Earthly Web. His *hun*-soul is imprisoned, his *po*-soul is struck; he is confined in the Three Bureaus. Yin and yang are blocked and separated, and this is no mere taboo of annihilation. In this year of exhaustion and severance, the very present moment is fraught with peril. The declines of the past have not yet been resolved, and new adversities have arisen. Calamities converge, and misfortune repeatedly befalls him. He is constantly beset by harm, and his household is in turmoil. Your disciple, at this very moment, is deeply unsettled, and his family, great and small, is filled with dread.

If not for the support of the Mysterious Ultimate and the advancement of life-saving aid, there would be no means to escape these profound disasters. If he does not petition the hidden bureaus and the perfected ones above to dispel these misfortunes, how can he avert these calamities? His entire household is filled with terror, and they turn their hearts toward the gate of benevolent protection. Bowing their heads to the Most Perfected, they pledge themselves beneath the incense and flame. With this petition, they beseech grace and entrust their lives to your servant.

The depth of their earnestness is truly pitiable; their sincerity is profound and weighty, and cannot be denied. Though your humble servant is foolish and ignorant, slow to comprehend the Mysterious Regulations, and though his shallow understanding cannot fathom their profound meaning, he has earnestly recounted these brief observations and sought to address the essential matters.

Moreover, he fears that your disciple’s *hun*-soul and *po*-soul have been seized and bewildered by the hundred ghosts, and that his name has been falsely recorded in the Black Register of the Right Palace, making it difficult to dissolve. Therefore, he humbly petitions the various departments of heavenly officials, lords, generals, officers, and soldiers, as enumerated below:

